<!DOCTYPE sub.page	SYSTEM "../Symbols.dtd">
<sub.page xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
	xmlns="http://webmath.math.ualberta.ca/v1/Book"
	xsi:schemaLocation="http://webmath.math.ualberta.ca/v1/Book    http://webmath.math.ualberta.ca/Schemas/v1/Book.xsd"
	id="Expla_OrthogonalProjection">
	<title>The Orthogonal Projections</title>
	<sub.page.body>
		<block>
			<para>Here we explain how to compute the orthogonal projection of <latex>\RNr[n]</latex> onto the 
				<subordinate>
					<hot>hyperspace</hot>
					<crossref>
						<definition.ref definitionID="Def_Hyperspace"/>
						<para>Look up the definition of a hyperspace</para>
					</crossref>
				</subordinate>
				<latex>H</latex> which is perpendicular to a nonzero vector <latex>\Vect{c}</latex>. We know that <latex>H</latex> consists of all those vectors <latex>\Vect{x}</latex> in <latex>\RNr[n]</latex> with <latex>\DotPr{\Vect{x}}{\Vect{c}}=0</latex>. The orthogonal projection <latex>P</latex> of <latex>\RNr[n]</latex> onto <latex>H</latex> transforms a point <latex>\Vect{x}</latex> in <latex>\RNr[n]</latex> into the point on <latex>H</latex> which is closest to <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>.</para>
			
			<figure>
				<img src="ims/OrthogonalProjection.png"></img><!-- svg available -->
			</figure>
			
			<para>Thus we find <latex>P(\Vect{x})</latex> by subtracting from <latex>\Vect{x}</latex> the 
				<subordinate>
					<hot>projection</hot>
					<crossref>
						<theorem.ref theoremID="Thm_ProjectionVectorOnLine"/>
						<para>Review this projection construction</para>
					</crossref>
				</subordinate>
				of <latex>\Vect{x}</latex> along <latex>\Vect{c}</latex>.
			</para>
			
			<math.display>
				<latex>P\from \RNr[n] \longrightarrow \RNr[n],\quad P(\Vect{x}) = \Vect{x}\ -\ \dfrac{\DotPr{\Vect{x}}{\Vect{c}}}{\DotPr{\Vect{c}}{\Vect{c}}} \cdot \Vect{c}</latex>
			</math.display>
		</block>
	</sub.page.body>
</sub.page>